    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3487734049" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3487734049" />
    <a title="Jennifer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18606111-jennifer"><img alt="Jennifer" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1403566107p2/18606111.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3487734049?book_show_action=true">Oct 07, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jennifer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jennifer" href="/user/show/18606111-jennifer">Jennifer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/20471037-tales-of-nev-r-on">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18606111-jennifer?shelf=lgbtq">lgbtq</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18606111-jennifer?shelf=slavery">slavery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18606111-jennifer?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3487734049" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12292881526170929329">A few years ago I read Delaney&apos;s Dhalgren and though it was deeply ugly and disturbing, the absolute brilliance of the construction of the world, and that it somehow described a reflection of a reflection of a reflection, blew my mind. Tales of Neveryon calls this construction out, teases about it, cautions and instructs us with respect to it, doubles down on it, brings it lightly and then heavily to our attention while also slipping it quietly by, all in the convincing guise of a series of entr</span>
  <span id="freeText12292881526170929329" style="display:none">A few years ago I read Delaney's Dhalgren and though it was deeply ugly and disturbing, the absolute brilliance of the construction of the world, and that it somehow described a reflection of a reflection of a reflection, blew my mind. Tales of Neveryon calls this construction out, teases about it, cautions and instructs us with respect to it, doubles down on it, brings it lightly and then heavily to our attention while also slipping it quietly by, all in the convincing guise of a series of entrancing interlocking stories interspersed with fictional academic musings (even these use reflection and refraction with the iteration of SLK). This is absolute mastery and just incredible genius. Its layers are symphonic, with all the math and beauty and iterated, complementary, refractive themes. Within all of this are threads - the roles and effects of money, credit, and commerce; sex, gender roles, and culture; the constructions of hierarchy and power; the unconscious force of the familiar in our thinking and understanding; cycles of, or iterations of, representation in art and words and math; conceptions of civilization and barbarism; the palimpsest. Delaney uses a dragons and princesses tale to focus on the warts, to digress into examinations of the things hidden or suppressed in most such stories, to tell us how those stories and all of our stories and histories reflect us and reflect back on us through refracted lenses. <br /><br />Among all the things I love about this book, there is something simpler, though also not simple, that I appreciated time and again in the reading: Delaney's feminism. The explorations here of gender-related power and influence, prestige, social roles, images and self-images, and the intersections of all of these things with socioeconomics and religion and politics and place. Gah, it's just so good. With respect to race, Delaney's barbarians are blond and easily identified in a crowd; the rest of the people are various shades of brown with kinky beards or black braids or other characteristics consistent with more, rather than less melanin. But, with the exception of the blond barbarians, everyone else in the stories is distinguished less by color than self-presentation (a purple dot on the chin, copper wires around the ears, hairstyles, language). This, too, this uncommented-on, normalized world of brown and browner people, is welcome and thought-provoking.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12292881526170929329" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

