    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4150968642" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4150968642" />
    <a title="Martin Keith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/126662732-martin-keith"><img alt="Martin Keith" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612135772p2/126662732.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4150968642?book_show_action=true">Aug 13, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Martin Keith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Martin Keith" href="/user/show/126662732-martin-keith">Martin Keith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/126662732-martin-keith?shelf=2021">2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4150968642" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5867863856058923004">This book is a hard recommend from me. Although touted as &quot;sword and sorcery&quot; <i>Tales of Nevèrÿon</i> only vaguely fits into that category. It barely even fits into &quot;fantasy&quot;, and only then because there are some dragons. &quot;Postmodern speculative fiction&quot; probably sums it up best. Nevèrÿon is a nation just crossing the brink of civilisation, and concepts like money are new and slavery is slowly becoming outdated. Through five short stories (and a prologue and epilogue written by fictional professors...</span>
  <span id="freeText5867863856058923004" style="display:none">This book is a hard recommend from me. Although touted as "sword and sorcery" <i>Tales of Nevèrÿon</i> only vaguely fits into that category. It barely even fits into "fantasy", and only then because there are some dragons. "Postmodern speculative fiction" probably sums it up best. Nevèrÿon is a nation just crossing the brink of civilisation, and concepts like money are new and slavery is slowly becoming outdated. Through five short stories (and a prologue and epilogue written by fictional professors...), Delany uses the blank slate of barely-civilisation to explore topics like slavery (and master-slave dynamics), feminism, sexuality and economics. He's particularly interested in the reflective nature of social phenomena (e.g. money is a <i>faithful</i> yet <i>flat</i> reflection of work and craft), and explores the ensuing effects on society.<br /><br />The book isn't particularly action-packed, and much of it composes conversations between the various characters. But the discussions are really interesting and are really the meat of the experience. This is because the characters themselves are interesting - they feel pretty human and down-to-earth and flawed in a way that "sword and sorcery" characters don't always. And the narrator's voice suits the book well - verbose when it needs to be, but not overly so - and makes its own comments on the stories. <br /><br />Overall <i>Tales of Nevèrÿon</i> kinda feels like <i>Conan the Barbarian</i>'s somewhat pretentious but genuinely insightful younger brother. The book is brimming with ideas and, more importantly, seems earnest to share them.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5867863856058923004" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

